Valentine Ranch, Rob & Kelly Valentine and family
June 12 at 3:17 PM Â·

It is beautiful outside today and I've been stuck inside baking for the majority of the day...but at least I have a good view! Those two girls in the background are our current family milkers, Alice and Rona. We bought the latter of the two this spring and decided naming her Rona would help us remember when we bought her, I mean 2020 and Corona will not soon be forgotten. ğŸ™ƒ

If you are a carb lover, be sure and come see me tomorrow at Market on the Square in Unionville from 7 til 11, cause I have ya covered! Fresh breads...French, Potato (the only traditional loaf white bread I make, try it & you'll see why) and Oatmeal (haven't brought this one to market this year, but it was well loved last year). Two choices of cookies, molasses and chocolate chip.

Fresh from the high tunnel will be swiss chard and kale and maybe a few other surprises.

The hens have a nice supply of eggs to bring in also. ğŸ”ğŸ¥š

I'll have a great selection of goat milk soap on hand as well.

Hope y'all can stop by tomorrow!

shared_text:
Valentine Ranch, Rob & Kelly Valentine and family
April 28 at 2:02 PM Â·

Do you know what true love is? True love is watching this strawberry ripen more each and every day and not picking it for myself...the very first one from our high tunnel and I'm saving it for my sweetheart. â¤

Fresh salad is on the menu for tonight's supper; along with some morel mushrooms. Our family loves to eat and we love to eat well! ğŸ˜ƒ I made a fresh batch of Greek yogurt yesterday with a gallon of raw cow milk. I ran out of time/energy at the end of the day and waited to strain it until today, if you haven't had "real" yogurt you are missing out. I reserved some for making more, left some plain and then used two cups to make one of Rob's favorite breakfasts...overnight oats with raisins, cinnamon and some other wholesome goodies that he doesn't even notice (chia & flax seeds).

Things here are growing well...two legged kids as well as four legged kids, and calves. Lots of fresh veggies are looking great and the hens and ducks are laying well too. New soaps are cured and ready to go. I LOVE this time of year! Farmers Market is just around the corner...anyone ready?
